Used Cars Price Prediction¶

Problem Definition¶

The Context:¶

  • There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.
  • In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones. Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

The objective:¶

  • Explore and analyze dataset
  • Perform Univariate and Bivariate analysis
  • Preprocess the data (fixing bad data/outlier treatment).
  • Build regression models to predict the prices of used cars.
  • Performance evaluation of model by RMSE.
  • Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

The key questions:¶

  • What Factors Influence Used Car Pricing?
  • Does Car Brand Affect Car Price?
  • How Does Transmission Type Impact Price?
  • Does Location Affect Car Price?
  • Is There a Correlation Between Kilometers Driven, Year of Manufacture, and Price?
  • How Does Mileage, Engine, and Power Affect Pricing? What's the Impact of Seating Capacity and Fuel Type on Pricing?

The problem formulation:¶

  • We are exploring and processing used car data and will be developing and comparing several models to best predict price given our features.

Data Dictionary¶

  • S.No. : Serial Number

  • Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name

  • Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (Cities)

  • Year : Manufacturing year of the car

  • Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM

  • Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

  • Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic / Manual)

  • Owner : Type of ownership

  • Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

  • Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC

  • Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp

  • Seats : The number of seats in the car

  • New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR 100,000

  • Price : The price of the used car in INR 100,000 (Target Variable)

#function to plot histplot and boxplot on shared axis
def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(8,1.5), kde=True,color=None):
    fig, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": [0.3, 0.7]}, figsize=figsize)

    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist,color=color)
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True,color=color)

    # Remove the boxplot x labels
    ax_box.set_xlabel('')
    ax_box.set_ylabel('')

    #removing space between plots
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0)

These seem like possible errors and with other outliers, we will winsorize them to make them closer to next most extreme values.

Outlier Treatment¶

In [ ]:
#creating a function that will winsorize or set extreme values closer to chosen quantile
def winsorize_by_group(df, group_col, winsorize_col,lower_quantile,upper_quantile):
    grouped = df.groupby(group_col,group_keys=True)

    def winsorize_group(group):
        lower_limit = group[winsorize_col].quantile(lower_quantile)
        upper_limit = group[winsorize_col].quantile(upper_quantile)
        group[winsorize_col] = group[winsorize_col].apply(lambda x: lower_limit if x < lower_limit else (upper_limit if x > upper_limit else x))
        return group
    #applying to df
    df = grouped.apply(winsorize_group)
    return df.reset_index(drop=True)

Handling NaNs¶

In [ ]:
#creating function that prints count and % of missing values per column if present
def missing_data(df):
    total = df.isnull().sum().sum()
    if total == 0:
        print("No missing values")
    else:
        for col in df.columns:
            count = df[col].isnull().sum()
            if count != 0:
                percent = count / len(df) * 100
                print(f"{col}............: {count} ({percent:.2f}%)")

#function for vif
def vif(x):
    vifdf = pd.DataFrame()
    x=sm.add_constant(x)
    vifdf["feature"] = x.columns
    # finding vif for each column
    vifdf["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(x.values, i) for i in range(x.shape[1])]
    return vifdf

#creating function to calculate rmse for train and test sets of given models
def calculate_rmse(models, X_train, y_train, preds, actuals):
    rmse_results = []

    for model in models:
        train_predics = model.predict(X_train)
        train_rmse = np.round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, train_predics)),5)
        test_predics = model.predict(preds)
        test_rmse = np.round(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(actuals, test_predics)),5)
        # appending RMSE to a list of results
        rmse_results.append({"Model": model.__class__.__name__,"Train_RMSE": train_rmse,"Val_RMSE": test_rmse})
    rmse_df = pd.DataFrame(rmse_results)
    return rmse_df
In [ ]:
def residual_plots(model,name, features, target):
    # getting preds and calculating avg error
    predictions = model.predict(features)
    actuals = target
    residuals = predictions - actuals
    avg_residual = residuals.mean()
    #creating subplot
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 5))
    # histogram on the first subplot
    sns.histplot(residuals, kde=True, bins=50,ax=axes[0])
    #residual plot as second subplot
    sns.residplot(x=predictions,y=residuals,lowess=True, scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.5},ax=axes[1])
    fig.suptitle(f'{name} | residual avg: {np.round(avg_residual,6)}', fontsize=16)
    plt.tight_layout();

Tuning & re-fitting Lasso/Ridge

In [ ]:
#function to perform cv on model, find its best alpha, and refit
def cv_linear_model(model, X_train, y_train, splits=10, random_state=462, score='neg_root_mean_squared_error', param_grid=None):
    if param_grid is None:
        param_grid = {'alpha':[0.001, 0.01, 0.1,.15, 0.2, 0.9, 1, 5, 10, 20,30]}

    folds = KFold(n_splits=splits, shuffle=True, random_state=random_state)
    model_cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid, scoring=score, cv=folds, return_train_score=True)
    start = time.time()
    model_cv.fit(X_train, y_train)
    optimal_params = model_cv.best_params_
    tuned_model = model.set_params(**optimal_params)
    tuned_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    stop = time.time()
    total = np.round(stop - start,2)
    print("Optimal Alpha:", optimal_params)
    print(f"Optimization & Training time: {total}s")
    return tuned_model

def n_features_importance_plot(model,name,top_n=15):
  features = list(X.columns)
  importances = model.feature_importances_
  # Create a DataFrame to store feature names and their importances
  feature_importance_df = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': features, 'Importance': importances})
  feature_importance_df = feature_importance_df.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)
  # Create a bar plot using Seaborn
  plt.figure(figsize=(18, 4))
  ax = sns.barplot(x='Importance', y='Feature', data=feature_importance_df.head(top_n), palette="light:b_r")
  ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0], label_type='edge',fmt='%.2f');
  plt.title(f'{name} | Top {top_n} Features');

Insights & Business Reccomendations

  • Power is one of the most important predictors of a car price. Higher valued cars are those with higher bhp. Mileage and Power are inversely related, meaning higher valued cars tend to have lower mileage.

  • Cars are known to depreciate, we can see that here in the model. Newer cars should be sought out with the intention to sell quicky to avoid depreciation while in inventory.

  • Cars with less owners tend to be more valuable and should be sought out over cars with more owners.

  • Cars with automatic transmissions should be sought out as they are on average worth more than those with manual transmissions.

  • Two seat cars on average are worth more than other seat configurations, likely due to them having higher power (sports cars).

  • Diesel and Electric cars should be sought out as they are on average more valuable than gas. Electric cars have a small footprint in the market but they serve as a possible foothold as they become increasingly popular.

  • The highest valued cars are in Coimbatore and Bangalore, but Bangalore has around 33% less used cars than Coimbatore, so it should be considered as an area for potential growth. Hyderabad is also a popular location for cars. Kolkata appears to be risky as it is one of the higher predictors for low value cars.

  • Mercedes-Benz, BMW, & Audi are the top 3 High-End brands by count. Honda, Toyota, & Volkswagen are the top 3 Mid-Level brands by count. These brands could be a potential targets for profitable transactions.

Business Risks & Considerations

  • Cars4U should consider missing factors that could affect car prices such as:

    • Previous accidents/salvaged & damage
    • Current mechanical condition
    • Maintenaince history
    • Condition of paint and exterior
    • Trim (AC, Sunroof, Bluetooth, leather, etc.)
    • Sets of keys

  • Cars considered lower value, (such as cars with lower power or cars that are gas powered) they shouldn't be completely excluded as potential purchases for resale. These cars, depending on asking price, can be purchased by Cars4U and re-sold at a gain. One benefit of the model is that it can give a predicted value of a car that can be compared to asking prices.

Proposal for the final solution design

  • XGBoost performs the best in terms of Root Mean Squared Error, meaning it will consistenly be more correct than the other models tested. The training time for XGBoost is slightly longer than that of the linear models, but is still considerably low.

  • This model will help to identify new trends as they come with time and will assist with predicitng/valuating a cars price, essentially giving Cars4u an opinion on whether a potential used car would be a promising when buying cars and profitable when selling cars.

Executive Summary

-High value cars are powerful, automatic, of certain brands, diesel powered

-There is potential room for growth in Bangalore and with Electric cars

-Important factors such as maintenance history should be researched and implemented for better insights and model prediction.

-XGBoost model can assist with profit-making decisions and validating trends
